-- Italian Stocks Decline; Autogrill Gains on Rating, Fondiaria Shares Drop
-- B y   A d a m   H a i g h
-- 2010-11-11T17:05:24Z
-- http://www.bloomberg.com/news/2010-11-11/italian-stocks-decline-autogrill-gains-on-rating-fondiaria-shares-drop.html
Italy’s benchmark  FTSE MIB Index 
declined 202.05, or 1 percent, to 20,855.96 at the 5:30 p.m.
close in Milan, a second day of losses.  The following stocks rose or fell in the Italian equity
market today.  Assicurazioni Generali SpA  (G IM), Europe’s third-biggest
insurer, said quarterly profit rose 13 percent as earnings at
its life-insurance unit increased. Net income climbed to 440
million euros ($602 million) in the third quarter from 390
million euros a year earlier, the company said in a statement.
That missed the 467 million-euro average estimate of 14 analysts
surveyed by Bloomberg. The stock fell 2.6 percent to 15.49
euros.  Autogrill SpA  (AGL IM) gained 2.5 percent to 9.96 euros.
UniCredit SpA raised its recommendation on shares of the world’s
biggest manager of airport and highway restaurants to “buy”
from “hold” and increased its price estimate by 18 percent to
11.30 euros, citing “surprisingly resilient margins” from its
third-quarter profit report yesterday.  Davide Campari-Milano SpA  (CPR IM), The maker of Wild
Turkey bourbon, said sales and earnings increased in the first
nine months of the year, aided by demand for spirits brands
including Skyy vodka. The stock rose 1.9 percent to 4.62 euros.  Fondiaria-Sai SpA  (FSA IM), Italy’s second biggest insurer,
lost 3.5 percent to 6.80 euros. Credit Suisse Group AG may
advise the Ligresti family in the planned capital increase of
Premafin Finanziaria SpA, which controls Fondiaria-Sai, La
Stampa reported without saying where it got the information.  To contact the reporter responsible for this story:
